## 5. Anti-Patterns to Avoid

> [!WARNING]
> These parallax patterns would **damage** the MMH brand experience.

| Anti-Pattern | Why It Breaks the Brand |
|---|---|
| Aggressive bounce/elastic parallax | Authority brands don't bounce. Stiffness damping should be high. |
| Full-screen background image parallax (classic "slow image scroll") | Dated. Associated with early 2010s sites. |
| Too many simultaneous parallax zones | Creates visual noise — kills the "gravitas" feeling. Max 2 active parallax zones per scroll position. |
| Parallax on typography at reading size | Hard to read moving text. Only use on large display text (h1/h2 size). |
| Directional inconsistency | Some elements going up while others go down destroys the narrative flow. Establish a consistent "upward drift = older content, entering = new content" convention. |

---

## 6. Implementation Principles

### The Monarch Parallax Doctrine

1. **Subtlety over spectacle** — Max offset is `120px` for any layer. Gold brands reveal depth; they don't scream.
2. **Gold leads, darkness follows** — When layering, the accent-colored element always has the highest speed multiplier (moves furthest = closest to user = most important).
3. **Spring damping ≥ 20** — All spring-animated parallax should use `damping: 20+` to avoid jitter. Matches brand's deliberate, controlled character.
4. **Scrub = narrative; spring = presence** — Use `ScrollTrigger.scrub` for story-driven scrollytelling. Use `useSpring` for mouse-interactive depth. Never mix the two on the same element.
5. **Never fight GSAP pins** — Do not add Framer Motion transforms to elements already controlled by GSAP ScrollTrigger pins (this caused past jitter in `ProblemsSection` ↔ `WhyInfotainment` boundary).

